                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If the 3 other mobs weren't mezzed, I died as soon as I cast my first heal.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Given that the likelihood of getting 4 waves in a row where you have at least 3 mezzable mobs is pretty low, that's kind of a recipe for failure don't you think?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Agro control? I guess I could have not healed the tank, but I don't see how much good that could have done.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Agro control is the job of the whole group, not just the healer. If you are in a situation where you are forced to cast a direct heal on someone with 3 uncontrolled mobs loose you have already lost control.
<br />

<br />
Mezzing is only one option, although it does tend to be the easiest one so lazy people often focus on it as if it's the only one. My point is that using this method in PoJ trials effectively cuts your dps by 1/6th. This was one of the reasons that most groups couldn't beat exe without a lot of luck.
<br />

<br />
Clerics had it much easier of course, they could just use SE and never get aggro. Of course, SE was brand new so I also had to talk my guild clerics into using it. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" />
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Anyway we had plenty of dps to succeed even with the enchanter mezzing.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This must have been more recent than when I was doing it. I remember people failing exe almost every time and panicing and trying different configurations. I got a bunch of my guilds groups through exe by recommending that they dropped their enc that they thought they had to have and get another dps class. (I also kept telling them to stop begging for banish classes. Banish was a stupid crutch that caused people to design groups that were almost certain to fail.)
<br />

<br />
Incidentially, people had the same problem with the trial of Fire. That trial is much easier if you ditch your enchanter who is adding very little dps and soaking up heal mana...
<br />

<br />
Of course nowdays I can go back and easily clear all the trials with 4 people (except fire)... heheh. Salute mudflation!</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
