                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Given that the likelihood of getting 4 waves in a row where you have at least 3 mezzable mobs is pretty low, that's kind of a recipe for failure don't you think? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Well we did fail, several times.  Mainly due to uncontrolled adds killing the healer.  I believe in one day we attempted the exec trial 6 times.  We succeeded on the sixth.  I died on 4 of the attempts.  On only one of the attempts did we lose due to low dps, and that was before we replaced the 63 wizard with a 65 mage.  On our successful attempt (this was back in February or March) we had a 61 paladin w/50ish aa, 62 enchanter (master title, not sure on aa), 61 or 62 rogue (I know he had veteran title, not sure on aa there either) 61 or 62 druid (venerable), 65 mage (sage) and me level 60 druid with 0 aa doing the healing (I was alt specced, other druid was evoc specced).   Later we did it on the 2nd attempt with a 65 SK, 60 cleric, 60 druid (me again), 60 enchanter, and I believe the same rogue and druid from the previous attempt, although we might have swapped one of them for a monk, I can't quite remember.
<br />

<br />
If I remember correctly only the rocks were unmezzable and these could be banished.  If we got one rock the tank got on it, two or three and  our banishers attempted to get rid of it, or the enchanter would charm it.    Four and we were pretty much screwed.  I remember a couple times managing to channel banish on the rock that immediately started beating on me after I healed the tank.  Luck was definately a big player, but compared to the horror stories I've heard from others, we did pretty well.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Mezzing is only one option, although it does tend to be the easiest one so lazy people often focus on it as if it's the only one. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
I really don't see how any other method would have been better for us.  Offtanking?  More mana expended healing that I could have used on nukes...plus we need everyone on the same mob in order to kill it fast enough.  Root?  Greater fetter costs more than GoK.  I guess you could use some low level root but those don't seem to last very long.  Plus if you root it too close to the melee then you end up healing them anyway, wasting mana.  If you root too far away then the melee waste time running to it when it's time to kill it.  Attempt to keep all four mobs on the tank?  Then the tank wouldn't really be able to hit anything, since he'd be constantly switching targets to cast on the mobs, and I'd still have to heal extra damage.  Charm?  yeah we used it in some of our attempts, but that only takes care of one mob.  I don't think Glamour of Kintaz is all that big of a mana burden.  I'd be surprised if an enchanter had no extra mana for nukes after keeping the mezzables mezzed in a trial attempt.   Anyway, I really don't see how we would have done better if the enchanter had forgone mezzing in favor of casting a 700pt nuke, or we had gotten another class instead.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=317219" target="_blank" class="postlink">Regane Der'driu</a>
<br />
Dark Elf Phantasmist, Veeshan server
<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">I am the voice inside your head,   and I control you.</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
